<article>
    <h1>Fix&#xAD;ing the noise</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200917/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-17"><time>2020-09-17</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline">Low Lin Fhoong</span>
    </section>

    <p>In a densely pop­u­lated coun­try like Sin­ga­pore, pro­posed fa­cil­i­ties like the Sailors’ train­ing cen­tre could run into some thorny is­sues.</p>
    <p>In De­cem­ber 2016, the use of two main foot­ball pitches at the Mat­tar Road lo­ca­tion – which was pre­vi­ously called the Home United Youth Foot­ball Acad­emy before it was taken over by the Sailors – was re­stricted to week­days before 7pm fol­low­ing com­plaints about noise lev­els from res­i­dents.</p>
    <p>A com­pro­mise then saw Home United be­ing al­lowed to con­duct train­ing and com­mu­nity en­gage­ment pro­grammes from 9am to 6pm on Satur­days and from 4pm to 7pm on Sun­days. Youth train­ing ac­tiv­i­ties were al­lowed from 7pm to 9pm on Mon­days and Wed­nes­days.</p>
    <p>Lion City Sailors Foot­ball Acad­emy gen­eral man­ager Tan Li Yu stressed that the club have been op­er­at­ing at Mat­tar Road for some time and that “ev­ery time a new field is built, one of the first con­sid­er­a­tions is what kind of im­pact it will have on res­i­dents”.</p>
    <p>Sound bar­ri­ers could be a so­lu­tion to help re­solve the noise is­sue, he added.</p>


